ChatGPT said:
‡¶†‡¶ø‡¶ï ‡¶Ü‡¶õ‡ßá‡•§ ‡¶§‡ßÅ‡¶Æ‡¶ø ‡¶ö‡¶æ‡¶á‡¶õ‡ßã WordPress ‡¶ö‡¶≤‡¶æ‡¶¨‡ßá ‡¶è‡¶¨‡¶Ç ‡¶®‡¶ø‡¶ú‡ßá‡¶∞ VPS-‡¶è SMTP mail server ‡¶∏‡ßá‡¶ü ‡¶ï‡¶∞‡¶¨‡ßá, ‡¶Ø‡¶æ‡¶§‡ßá ‡¶®‡¶ø‡¶ú‡ßá‡¶∞ ‡¶°‡ßã‡¶Æ‡ßá‡¶á‡¶® ‡¶•‡ßá‡¶ï‡ßá ‡¶á‡¶Æ‡ßá‡¶á‡¶≤ ‡¶™‡¶æ‡¶†‡¶æ‡¶§‡ßá ‡¶™‡¶æ‡¶∞‡ßã‡•§ ‡¶Ü‡¶Æ‡¶ø ‡¶ß‡¶æ‡¶™‡ßá ‡¶ß‡¶æ‡¶™‡ßá guide ‡¶¶‡¶ø‡¶ö‡ßç‡¶õ‡¶ø, Oracle Free Tier (Always Free / Free Trial) instance ‡¶ß‡¶∞‡ßá‡•§

Step 1: VPS Instance ‡¶§‡ßà‡¶∞‡¶ø ‡¶ï‡¶∞‡¶æ
Always Free Limit ‡¶Ö‡¶®‡ßÅ‡¶Ø‡¶æ‡¶Ø‡¶º‡ßÄ (4 OCPUs + 24 GB RAM, 200 GB storage)

1 instance ‡¶¨‡¶æ‡¶®‡¶æ‡¶¨‡ßá Ubuntu 22.04 LTS Minimal (arm64)

RAM: 4‚Äì8 GB (WordPress + mail server smooth ‡¶ö‡¶æ‡¶≤‡¶æ‡¶®‡ßã‡¶∞ ‡¶ú‡¶®‡ßç‡¶Ø)

Storage: 50‚Äì100 GB (WordPress + DB + Mail)

Public IP assign ‡¶ï‡¶∞‡¶¨‡ßá

Note: 1 instance-‡¶è WordPress + mail server ‡¶è‡¶ï‡¶∏‡¶æ‡¶•‡ßá ‡¶ö‡¶≤‡ßá, ‡¶ï‡¶ø‡¶®‡ßç‡¶§‡ßÅ ‡¶Ø‡¶¶‡¶ø heavy traffic ‡¶Ü‡¶∂‡¶æ ‡¶ï‡¶∞‡ßã ‡¶§‡¶æ‡¶π‡¶≤‡ßá 2 instance ‡¶Ü‡¶≤‡¶æ‡¶¶‡¶æ ‡¶ï‡¶∞‡¶æ ‡¶≠‡¶æ‡¶≤‡ßã‡•§

Step 2: WordPress Environment Install ‡¶ï‡¶∞‡¶æ
Apache + PHP + MariaDB install

sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y
sudo apt install apache2 php libapache2-mod-php php-mysql mariadb-server php-cli php-curl php-gd php-mbstring php-xml php-xmlrpc php-soap php-intl php-zip unzip -y
MariaDB secure setup

sudo mysql_secure_installation
WordPress download & setup

cd /var/www/html
sudo wget https://wordpress.org/latest.tar.gz
sudo tar -xvzf latest.tar.gz
sudo mv wordpress/* .
sudo chown -R www-data:www-data /var/www/html
sudo chmod -R 755 /var/www/html
Database create for WordPress

sudo mysql -u root -p
CREATE DATABASE wpdb;
CREATE USER 'wpuser'@'localhost' IDENTIFIED BY 'StrongPassword123!';
GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON wpdb.* TO 'wpuser'@'localhost';
FLUSH PRIVILEGES;
EXIT;
Apache config

sudo nano /etc/apache2/sites-available/wordpress.conf
Add:

<VirtualHost *:80>
    ServerName yourdomain.com
    DocumentRoot /var/www/html
    <Directory /var/www/html>
        AllowOverride All
    </Directory>
</VirtualHost>
Enable site:

sudo a2ensite wordpress.conf
sudo a2enmod rewrite
sudo systemctl restart apache2
Step 3: Mail Server Setup (SMTP)
Recommended lightweight option: Postfix + Dovecot (SMTP + IMAP/POP3)

Install Postfix & Dovecot

sudo apt install postfix dovecot-core dovecot-imapd -y
Postfix configuration

Type: Internet Site

System mail name: yourdomain.com

Dovecot configuration (IMAP)

sudo nano /etc/dovecot/dovecot.conf
Enable IMAP:

protocols = imap
Set up Mailboxes

sudo useradd -m wpmail
sudo passwd wpmail
Allow WordPress to send emails via SMTP

Install WP Mail SMTP plugin

Configure with:

SMTP Host: yourdomain.com

SMTP Port: 587

Encryption: STARTTLS

SMTP User: wpmail@yourdomain.com

SMTP Password: the password you set

Step 4: DNS Records
A record ‚Üí yourdomain.com points to VPS IP

MX record ‚Üí yourdomain.com points to yourdomain.com

SPF record (TXT) ‚Üí allow your VPS to send mail

v=spf1 mx ~all
DKIM (optional but recommended)

Use opendkim to sign outgoing mails

Step 5: Test
WordPress ‚Üí send test email via WP Mail SMTP

Check mail logs:

sudo tail -f /var/log/mail.log
üí° Tip:

Always Free instance CPU 4 cores + RAM 24 GB ‚Üí WordPress + Mail server ‡¶è‡¶ï‡¶∏‡¶æ‡¶•‡ßá smooth ‡¶ö‡¶≤‡¶¨‡ßá‡•§

Mail server setup ‡¶π‡¶≤‡ßá ensure port 25, 587, 465 open in Oracle Cloud VCN/firewall.

‡¶Ø‡¶¶‡¶ø ‡¶ö‡¶æ‡¶ì, ‡¶Ü‡¶Æ‡¶ø ‡¶§‡ßã‡¶Æ‡¶æ‡¶∞ ‡¶ú‡¶®‡ßç‡¶Ø ‡¶è‡¶ï‡¶ü‡¶æ ‡¶∏‡¶Æ‡ßç‡¶™‡ßÇ‡¶∞‡ßç‡¶£ ready-to-run command script ‡¶¨‡¶æ‡¶®‡¶æ‡¶§‡ßá ‡¶™‡¶æ‡¶∞‡¶ø, ‡¶Ø‡¶æ ‡¶è‡¶ï‡¶¨‡¶æ‡¶∞‡ßá WordPress + Postfix SMTP server setup ‡¶ï‡¶∞‡¶¨‡ßá, ‡¶è‡¶¨‡¶Ç SSL + firewall automatically configure ‡¶ï‡¶∞‡¶¨‡ßá‡•§

